docs.abstract: His decidedly eclectic board game became a familiar part of American family life in the late 1990s and 2000s.
docs.snippet: His decidedly eclectic board game became a familiar part of American family life in the late 1990s and 2000s.
docs.lead_paragraph: Richard Tait, an entrepreneur, business executive and venture capitalist who helped invent the board game Cranium, a familiar part of American family life in the late 1990s and 2000s, died on July 25 at his home in Bainbridge Island, Wash. He was 58.

headline.main: Richard Tait, Co-Inventor of the Board Game Cranium, Dies at 58
headline.print_headline: Richard Tait, 58, Co-Inventor  Of the Board Game Cranium

docs.abstract: The sale, which is expected to be the biggest in auction history for a private collection, will offer works from the Microsoft co-founder’s impressive cache that ranges from old masters to contemporary giants.
docs.snippet: The sale, which is expected to be the biggest in auction history for a private collection, will offer works from the Microsoft co-founder’s impressive cache that ranges from old masters to contemporary giants.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the art world’s latest eye-popping development, Christie’s auction house announced on Thursday that it would sell the impressive art collection of Paul G. Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft who died in 2018. The trove, which includes masterpieces by Renoir and Roy Lichtenstein, has an estimated valued of more than $1 billion.

headline.main: Christie’s to Sell Paul G. Allen’s $1 Billion Art Collection
headline.print_headline: Christie’s to Sell Art Trove Of Microsoft Co-Founder

docs.abstract: The Green Bay Packers are the only N.F.L. team whose fans can buy an ownership stake. Their annual shareholders meeting is part pep rally, part window into the league’s finances.
docs.snippet: The Green Bay Packers are the only N.F.L. team whose fans can buy an ownership stake. Their annual shareholders meeting is part pep rally, part window into the league’s finances.
docs.lead_paragraph: GREEN BAY, Wis. — It takes a certain type of Packers fan to tailgate outside Lambeau Field at sunrise months before the team’s season kicks off. But Tom Rozum isn’t an ordinary fan: He’s a Packers shareholder who last month was preparing to attend the team’s annual shareholder meeting, a rite unique to the N.F.L.’s only publicly owned team.

headline.main: How Much Do N.F.L. Teams Make? Packers Fans Paid to Find Out.
headline.print_headline: ‘Today, You Can Walk Around Like You Own the Place’
